[1] Cholera - Iraq
Date: Tue 23 Oct 2007
Source: UN Integrated Regional Information Networks (IRIN) [edited]
<http://reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/LRON-789J29?OpenDocument&rc=3&cc=irq>


UN agencies and the Iraqi government say the cholera outbreak is
under control, despite the fact that since August 2007 there have
been about 4200 laboratory-confirmed cases and 21 deaths from the disease.

"Iraqis have adhered to the rules to guarantee their safety against
cholera and numbers have dropped dramatically; in addition, more than
70 percent of reported cases are being treated with success," said
Taha Abdallah, a senior official at the Ministry of Health. "There
are some areas where sanitation is poor and there is a deficit of
potable water, leaving residents in a more dangerous situation, but
we are working hard to contain the problem. And with the end of the
summer season, the possible spread of the disease is lower," Abdallah
added. "An intense campaign was developed among displaced families to
prevent the spread of the disease among the most vulnerable."

The UN Children's Fund (UNICEF) and World Health Organization (WHO)
are urgently calling on all Iraqis to follow the preventive measures,
which are simple and affordable and have proved to be effective in
warding off the risk of a cholera outbreak. So far 39 districts in 11
provinces have been affected, according to the Ministry of Health.

Shoubo Rasheed, UNICEF's communication specialist, said: "Reduction
in the number of cholera cases and deaths does not happen by chance.
However, each and every Iraqi can make a significant contribution to
combating the outbreak simply by following the rules of food, water,
and personal hygiene."

Kirkuk, Sulaymaniyah, Erbil, Dohuk, Tikrit, Mosul, Diyala, Basra,
Wasit, Baghdad, and Anbar provinces are affected by the cholera
outbreak. "Local health units have been struggling to stop the
disease from spreading and have obtained excellent results," Abdallah said.

Despite a decline in the number of cholera cases, both UNICEF and WHO
have continued their support for local health units by providing
technical support, training on case management, outbreak
investigation, and containment. The 2 UN agencies have also been
supporting awareness and hygiene promotion campaigns in the country.

--
